`scripts/` implements Layer 1 of the project's CI gate: static/quality checks that run against the Rust workspace, orchestrated so that all checks execute and report regardless of individual failures. Depending on this directory means invoking `ci.sh` as the single entry point (from CI or pre-commit); everything else here is either a check `ci.sh` calls or an unrelated setup utility (`install-tools.sh`).

`ci.sh` is the authoritative list of what "Layer 1" means — its `RUN` sequence is the sole place a check is added, removed, or reordered. It runs upstream cargo checks (fmt, clippy, doc, deny, machete) inline, then shells out to four repo-local scripts resolved via its own `SCRIPTS_DIR`: `rationale_check.py`, `workspace_lints_check.sh`, `no_allow_check.sh`, `cycle_check.sh`. Any new check script must be added there and must accept the same argument convention the others do (`.`-relative root, except `cycle_check.sh` which takes none).

Three of the check scripts (`no_allow_check.sh`, `workspace_lints_check.sh`, `rationale_check.py`) share a load-bearing enumeration pattern: `git ls-files -z --cached --others --exclude-standard` instead of a filesystem walk, specifically to avoid racing a concurrent `target/` build directory and to keep results a pure function of tracked/untracked-but-not-ignored repo state. Changing that enumeration in one script without the others reintroduces the race it was designed to avoid. `no_allow_check.sh` and `workspace_lints_check.sh` also share the "require git work tree, else exit 1" precondition and per-manifest/per-file `FAIL:` accumulation-not-short-circuit style, matching `ci.sh`'s own non-short-circuiting philosophy.

`cycle_check.sh` and `rationale_check.py` are both explicitly named as MVP stand-ins for a future dylint rule set (`docs/DYLINT_RULES.md`); `cycle_check.sh` in particular does **not** actually detect cycles yet — it only verifies `cargo-modules` runs, so anyone relying on it for real cycle detection gets a false pass. `machete_check.sh` is referenced by name in `docs/SPEC.md`'s dependency policy but its enforcement is invoked from within `ci.sh` via `cargo deny`/`cargo machete` directly, not as one of the four delegated scripts — check `ci.sh`'s RUN list, not this file, for the true call graph. `install-tools.sh` is unrelated to the check pipeline: it's the sync mechanism pulling `ctx-*` binaries and summarizer prompts from a sibling tooling repo, and is the only place binary/package lists for that repo are kept (manually, not automatically) in sync.